observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed that:
The Disbursing Officer prepare the estimates of expenses to be paid out of the cash advance in compliance with COA Circular No. 97-002. Moreover, to avoid granting of excessive cash advances, the Municipal Accountant must ensure that the disbursement vouchers for cash advances on petty miscellaneous expenses are supported by estimates of petty miscellaneous expenses to be paid out of cash advance; 
The Disbursing Officer submit the Report of Disbursements for cash disbursements for CY 2014 and ensure to attach it in the liquidation of cash advances; 
The Municipal Accountant submit promptly and regularly all paid payrolls as well as approved daily time records (DTRs), approved application for leave, and other pertinent supporting documents pursuant to Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree 1445 and Section 5.10.1 of COA Circular 97-002 dated February 10, 1997, as reiterated in Section 1.2.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and
Management explain why the disbursing officer is not an employee of the Municipal Treasurer’s Office.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant:
Refrain from granting CA intended for continuous travel;
Closely monitor the use of CAs by the officials and employees;
Remind the employees concerned to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed period provided in Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Require complete documentation before recording the liquidation of CAs;
Strictly comply with COA Circular No. 2012-001;
Ensure that the Liquidation Reports are pre-numbered and with date of liquidation; and
See to it that the amount in the DV for reimbursement will only reflect the amount to be reimbursed.
Municipal Mayor require the officials and employees to refrain from using the CAs for purposes other than what is intended for; and
Concerned officials and employees to:
Refund immediately the unexpended CAs,
Attach the official receipt for the refunded excess CA in the liquidation of their CAs and;
Submit the original copy of ORs of their refunds to the Accounting Department and thereafter forward the same to COA for audit purposes.

We recommended that:
Management pursue the timely submission of the accounts with all receipts and paid disbursement vouchers and their supporting documents, as well as the above-cited reports, within the prescribed period to avoid the automatic suspension of the payment of salary and other emoluments, and the imposition of administrative disciplinary action upon the defaulting concerned personnel; 
Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Engineer to prepare the monthly monitoring report of the awarded infra PPAs, as well as the list of Ongoing PPAs, and those that are to be implemented during the year in accordance with COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013; 
Designated General Service Officer together with the concerned Department Heads accountable for the Inventory Items to conduct semestral physical count of inventories and submit the report in compliance with Section 124 of the MNGAS, Volume I; 
Municipal Accountant make representation with the depository banks or send follow-up letters for failure of banks to furnish the bank statements on time; and 
OIC-Municipal Treasurer ensure the timely transmittal of the monthly report of collections together with copies of official s receipts and validated deposit slips to the Office of the Municipal Accountant for recording purposes.

We recommended that the:
OIC-Municipal Accountant and the ICO Municipal Treasurer analyze the reconciling items identified in the bank reconciliation statements and make necessary adjustments pertaining thereto; 
ICO-Municipal Treasurer make representation with the bank regarding the unrecorded credit memo(s) and obtain copy of the credit memo and to ascertain the purpose for which the fund was given; 
OIC-Municipal Accountant provide details of the outstanding checks in order for the audit team to verify the period for which the checks are outstanding.
Instruct all collectors to remit their collections intact and daily before the close of office hours to the Liquidating Officer pursuant to Section 31 of NGAS Manual for LGU Volume I; 
Instruct the Liquidating Officer to deposit intact all collections turned-over to her on the same day or the next banking day to minimize exposure to risk of possible loss pursuant to Section 32 of MNGAS for LGU Volume I; 
Ensure that only bonded employees will be assigned in collecting function of the Treasurer’s Office pursuant to the provision of Section 101 of PD 1445, Section 305(f) of RA 7160, Section 50, Chapter 9, Subtitle B, Book V, EO No 292 and Bureau of Treasury, Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 dated August 5, 2009.
